> Ok, so where do we start?  How do we ensure that our equipment is serving our business?

---

Every printer make has some sort of networked interface to fulfill its duty as a printer and provide data points about its operating status and parameters.

|   |   |
|---|---|
| [Zebra Programming Guide](https://www.zebra.com/content/dam/zebra/manuals/printers/common/programming/zpl-zbi2-pm-en.pdf) | This guide is the unabridged, alphabetical reference of programming commands supported in the firmware. This includes all ZPL commands and SGD commands. |
| [SATO API](https://www.sato-global.com/files/Integration_Options/SATO_Printer_API/UM_SATOPrinterAPI_EN.pdf) | Software developers can use this API to send printer commands to the printer as well as to receive a response from the printer if there is any.  |
| [Printronix PXML](https://printronix.com/wp-content/uploads/manuals/PTX_PRM_PXML_253343B.pdf) | This manual describes a communication model for remotely managing Printronix printers. It is for application developers to implement custom printer management schemes. |
| [Honeywell Mobility SDK](https://sps.honeywell.com/us/en/software/productivity/development-tools/mobility-sdk-windows) | Build innovative applications for Honeywell computers, printers, and RFID that incorporate the latest mobile, communication and data collection technologies. |

We're in luck.  It seems that every printer make is capable of communicating over a TCP/IP network.  

```diagram

```

We'll focus on a Zebra implemenation because it is most straight forward exchange of ASCII characters over a TCP/IP socket. 

---

Two basic things we want to know about our printer is whether it's online and its health.  'Online' could mean a lot of things, but in the context of the printer's ability to serve print requests we'll settle for a successful response to a PING request over the network.

```diagram

```


An [Event](https://model.mtconnect.org/#Architecture__578514fe-2c65-4428-a2a6-77dd0059b660) category data item of [AVAILABILITY](https://model.mtconnect.org/#Architecture__efa904df-e614-4dde-81d4-3d9d41ea5596) type will represent our ability to communicate with the printer.  An event contains a finite number of states.

> An EVENT is a data item representing a discrete piece of information from the piece of equipment. EVENT does not have intermediate values that vary over time, as does SAMPLE. An EVENT is information that, when provided at any specific point in time, represents the current state of the piece of equipment.
{.is-info}

> Event Type AVAILABILITY - Represents the Agents ability to communicate with the data source.
{.is-info}


```diagram

```

```xml
<!-- info model -->
<DataItem category="EVENT" id="avail" type="AVAILABILITY"/>
```

Next we need the general health of the printer. Here is an example of a host status command response. The printer is indeed in an error state.

![printer1.png](/world_of_printers/printer1.png)

To be more precise, the printer is in an error state, head is open, and it is paused.

![printer2.png](/world_of_printers/printer2.png)

A [Condition](https://model.mtconnect.org/#Architecture__b5a9fb61-fd07-4e9d-a7a5-83ead254c35d) category data item of [SYSTEM](https://model.mtconnect.org/#Architecture__20946092-12aa-4baa-84dd-d38ed684782f) type will represent the overall health of the printer.

> A CONDITION is a data item that communicates information about the health of a piece of equipment and its ability to function. A valid value for a data item in the category CONDITION can be one of Normal, Warning, or Fault.
{ .is-info }

> Condition Type SYSTEM: An indication of a fault associated with a piece of equipment or component that cannot be classified as a specific type.
{ .is-info }

```xml
<!-- info model -->
<DataItem category="CONDITION" id="system_cond" type="SYSTEM"/>
```

Below are the possible states for a Condition.  Just like Event and Sample categories, the initial value is 'UNAVAILABLE'... until it isn't.

> If at any time an Agent loses communications with a piece of equipment, or the Agent is unable to determine a valid value for all, or any portion, of the Data Entities published by a piece of equipment, the Agent MUST place an occurrence of each of these Data Entities in the buffer with its value set to UNAVAILABLE. This signifies that the value is currently indeterminate and no assumptions of a valid value for the data is possible.
{ .is-info }

```diagram

```

While we are here, let's also capture a [Sample](https://model.mtconnect.org/#Architecture__250db264-50ad-4338-bbab-9d118ff84461) category data item, or a continuously changing value like an odometer.

> A SAMPLE is the reading of the value of a continuously variable or analog data value. A continuous value can be measured at any point-in-time and will always produce a result.
{ .is-info }

![printer3.png](/world_of_printers/printer3.png)

Printed meters are best captured as an [actual position](https://model.mtconnect.org/#Architecture__616a116b-4d08-45ae-8abc-97b7902c86c2) with a conversion scale of 0.001 to be represented in millimeters.

> Sample Type POSITION - A measured or calculated position of a Component element as reported by a piece of equipment.
{ .is-info }

```xml
<!-- info model -->
<DataItem category="SAMPLE" id="life_odometer" type="POSITION"
          subType="ACTUAL"
          nativeScale="0.001"
          units="MILLIMETER"/>
```

Ok, so putting the above pieces of information together, we arrive at a model like this.

```xml
<!-- info model -->
<Devices>
 <Device name="printer1" uuid="18J175305721">
  <DataItems>
   <DataItem category="EVENT" id="avail" type="AVAILABILITY"/>
   <DataItem category="CONDITION" id="system_cond" type="SYSTEM"/>
   <DataItem category="SAMPLE" id="life_odometer" type="POSITION"
          subType="ACTUAL"
          nativeScale="0.001"
          units="MILLIMETER"/>
  </DataItems>
 </Device>
</Devices>
```

In its simplest form, this model is transferable across Zebra, SATO, Printronix, and Honeywell.  The exercise for you is to find relevant data points across manufacturers to satisfy this model. 

We can now bring this model to life with a single visualization over the unified model using a controlled vocabulary.

```diagram

```

Let me repeat that once more.  You build one dashboard, over a single information model, modeled over four different manufacturers of hardware.
